England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Newland, Glou., Eng.":"Newland, Gloucestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England":"Clearwell, Gloucestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1220–":"omkring 1220–Afdød","1220–Male":"1220–Afdød","1230–1282":"1230–1282","1224–Female":"1224–Afdød","1245–Male":"1245–Afdød","1247–Female":"1247–Afdød","1253–1337":"1253–1337","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1204–Female":"1204–Afdød","1253":"1253","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1282":"1282","abt 1245":"omkring 1245","1238":"1238","abt 1247":"omkring 1247","1337":"1337","1204":"1204","1247":"1247","um 1253":"omkring 1253","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","about 1220":"omkring 1220","Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Newland, Glou., Eng.":"Newland, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England":"Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1220–":"circa 1220–Overleden","1220–Male":"1220–Overleden","1230–1282":"1230–1282","1224–Female":"1224–Overleden","1245–Male":"1245–Overleden","1247–Female":"1247–Overleden","1253–1337":"1253–1337","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1204–Female":"1204–Overleden","1253":"1253","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1282":"1282","abt 1245":"circa 1245","1238":"1238","abt 1247":"circa 1247","1337":"1337","1204":"1204","1247":"1247","um 1253":"circa 1253","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","about 1220":"circa 1220","Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Clearwell, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Newland, Glou., Eng.":"Newland, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England":"Clearwell, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1220–":"about 1220–Deceased","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1230–1282":"1230–1282","1224–Female":"1224–Deceased","1245–Male":"1245–Deceased","1247–Female":"1247–Deceased","1253–1337":"1253–1337","1200–1245":"1200–1245","1204–Female":"1204–Deceased","1253":"1253","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1282":"1282","abt 1245":"about 1245","1238":"1238","abt 1247":"about 1247","1337":"1337","1204":"1204","1247":"1247","um 1253":"about 1253","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1200":"1200","about 1220":"about 1220","Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Newland, Glou., Eng.":"Newland, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England":"Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joyce","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Bridie, Declan, Eamon, Kieran, Liam, Brian Patrick, Conor, Cormac, John Patrick, Nuala, Siobhan.","English: principally from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Joce</i>, <i>Josse</i>, <i>Joice</i>, a Romance form of Old Breton <i>Iuthoc</i>, a pet form of a name in <i>Iuth-</i> ‘lord’ with the hypocoristic suffix <i>-oc</i>. <i>Joce</i> became popular as a personal name, especially in medieval Picardy, Artois, Normandy, and Flanders, through the cult of Saint Josse. According to legend, he was the brother or son of the 7th-century Breton king Judhael (see   Jewell  ), and gave up his inheritance to become a hermit in the place recorded in the 8th century as <i>Sanctus Jodocus</i>, now Saint-Josse-sur-Mer, near Étaples in Pas-de-Calais. The cult was promoted in the second half of the 8th century by the Frankish king Charlemagne, and was brought to England (Winchester) in the early 10th century by refugees from Saint-Josse, the centre of the cult, but use of the personal name in England is not known until after the Norman Conquest. Middle English <i>Joce</i> also was sometimes used as a female name (as <i>Joyce</i> is in modern times) and this may have also given rise to a surname.","English: sometimes a variant of   Goss  , from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gozzo</i>, <i>Gauz</i>, which often became <i>Joce</i>, <i>Joice</i>, <i>Joss(e)</i> in Old French. It was frequently used as a short form of <i>Goscelin</i> or <i>Joscelin</i> (see   Joslin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Joice","meanings":["English: variant of   Joyce  ."]},{"name":"Choice","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Joyce  . There is a family tradition among bearers of the name that it means ‘chosen’, from Middle English, Old French <i>chois</i> (of ancient Germanic origin). In the Middle Ages the word was used both for an ‘act of choosing’ and a ‘thing chosen’, and as an adjective with the meaning ‘chosen’, ‘select, favored’. Perhaps this word gave rise to a nickname, but there is no evidence to support this speculation."]},{"name":"Choyce","meanings":["variant of   Joyce  .","alternatively, in some instances it may be a nickname derived from Middle English (Old French) <i>chois</i> ‘handsome (person)’.","English:"]},{"name":"Jewell","meanings":["English (Devon and Cornwall): from an Old Breton personal name, <i>Iudhael</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘lord’ + ‘generous, bountiful’ (see   Jewkes  ), which was borne by a 7th-century Christian saint, a king of Brittany who abdicated and spent the last part of his life in a monastery. Forms of this name are found in medieval records not only in Devon and Cornwall, where they are of native origin, but also in East Anglia and even Yorkshire, where they were imported by Bretons after the Norman Conquest. The name was seemingly reintroduced from France in the 17th century by Huguenots."]},{"name":"Jost","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Hans, Aloys, Erna, Erwin, Hans Peter, Heinz, Inge, Jurgen, Mathias, Reinhart.","German (also <b>Jöst</b>) and Dutch: from a personal name, a derivative of Old French <i>Josse</i>, from Breton <i>Iodoc</i>, Latinized as <i>Jodocus</i> (see   Joyce  ). It can also be from the personal name   Just  , Latin <i>Justus</i>. The surname <i>Jost</i> is also found in Poland and Slovenia (compare with the form <b>Jošt</b> below).","Slovenian and Czech (<b>Jošt</b>): from a personal name derived from German <i>Jost</i> and this one from <i>Jodocus</i>, the Latinized name of a Christian saint (see   Joyce  , compare 1 above)."]},{"name":"Joss","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Fritz, Kurt, Otto.","Scottish and German: from an Old French personal name derived from Breton <i>Iodoc</i>, Latinized as <i>Jodocus</i> (see   Joyce  ).","English: possibly from a Middle English pet form of   Joseph  , but this is not confirmed by medieval evidence."]},{"name":"Jossart","meanings":["Walloon and French: from a derivative of the Old French personal name <i>Josse</i>, from Breton <i>Iodoc</i>, Latinized as <i>Jodocus</i> (see   Joyce  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Joyce was born about 1220, in Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Joyce of St Briavels, was 22 and his mother, Unknown, was 18. He married Lady Ellen de Button in 1238, in Clearwell, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"about 1220–":"umbes 1220–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1230–1282":"1230–1282","1224–Female":"1224–Surnud","1245–Male":"